{"parentUuid":"b3181a46-7844-4e45-8981-c714f892c2e5","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01SoJYfKNFcUDodx2zHHcMka","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01R21BieAePPsgsXzh35StWS","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"sample size two proportions 80% power table absolute difference"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5902,"cache_read_input_tokens":6421,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5902,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":8281}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFqJfeXMXPcWpyhW3ihL","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"106ed2e3-9fed-4b4b-9137-8121d913156a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:52.520Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"106ed2e3-9fed-4b4b-9137-8121d913156a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01R21BieAePPsgsXzh35StWS","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"sample size two proportions 80% power table absolute difference\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"power twoproportions — Power analysis for a two-sample proportions test\",\"url\":\"https://www.stata.com/manuals/pss-2powertwoproportions.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Comparing Two Proportions - Sample Size - Select Statistical Consultants\",\"url\":\"https://select-statistics.co.uk/calculators/sample-size-calculator-two-proportions/\"},{\"title\":\"Sample size calculation: comparison of two proportions | MedCalc\",\"url\":\"https://www.medcalc.org/en/manual/sample-size-comparison-of-proportions.php\"},{\"title\":\"Sample Size Estimation - Compare Two Proportions\",\"url\":\"https://www2.ccrb.cuhk.edu.hk/stat/proportion/Casagrande.htm\"},{\"title\":\"Pertussis Challenge Study in Adults Vaccinated With BPZE1\",\"url\":\"https://cdn.clinicaltrials.gov/large-docs/31/NCT05461131/SAP_001.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Sample size estimation v. 2018-02\",\"url\":\"https://www.bioinformatics.babraham.ac.uk/training/Introduction_to_Power_Analysis/Sample%20Size%20estimation%20Course%20slides.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Power and Sample Size Determination - sph.bu.edu\",\"url\":\"https://sphweb.bumc.bu.edu/otlt/mph-modules/bs/bs704_power/BS704_Power8.html\"},{\"title\":\"Sample Size Calculation: Power, Errors & Clinical Trials | IntuitionLabs\",\"url\":\"https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/sample-size-calculation-clinical-trials\"},{\"title\":\"Sample Size Calculator & Statistical Power Calculator\",\"url\":\"https://www.gigacalculator.com/calculators/power-sample-size-calculator.php\"},{\"title\":\"ADJUnct Semaglutide Treatment in Type 1 Diabetes\",\"url\":\"https://cdn.clinicaltrials.gov/large-docs/33/NCT05537233/Prot_SAP_001.pdf\"}]\n\nI've found relevant information about sample size calculations for comparing two proportions with 80% power. Here's what the search results show:\n\n## Key Concepts\n\nIf your power is 80%, then this means that you have a 20% probability of failing to detect a significant difference when one does exist, i.e., a false negative result (otherwise known as type II error).\n\n## Sample Size Calculation Approach\n\nFor a power of 80%, β is 0.2 and the critical value is 0.84, and this is used in calculations with the expected sample proportions of the two groups.\n\n## Practical Examples\n\nThe search results include several examples:\n\n1. If aiming for a decrease from 40% to 10% for tumour development, approximately 2 samples of about 36 subjects would be needed to reach significance (p<0.05) with 80% power.\n\n2. Using Fisher's exact test at an alpha level of 0.05, a sample size of 32 per group is expected to have power close to 80% to detect a 30% difference in the proportion of participants if the proportion in the control group is 5%.\n\nThe results also reference comprehensive references like Machin et al. (2009) \"Sample size tables for clinical studies,\" which contains detailed tables for various combinations of Type I and Type II error levels. For specific tables with varying absolute differences, you may want to consult that reference or use statistical software like G*Power, Stata, or online calculators that can generate tables for your specific parameters.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"32d6c966-7e84-45e4-9589-7fc839552d55","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:03.517Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"sample size two proportions 80% power table absolute difference","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01DBACLCGegYzSZp3ipTBPKx","content":[{"title":"power twoproportions — Power analysis for a two-sample proportions test","url":"https://www.stata.com/manuals/pss-2powertwoproportions.pdf"},{"title":"Comparing Two Proportions - Sample Size - Select Statistical Consultants","url":"https://select-statistics.co.uk/calculators/sample-size-calculator-two-proportions/"},{"title":"Sample size calculation: comparison of two proportions | MedCalc","url":"https://www.medcalc.org/en/manual/sample-size-comparison-of-proportions.php"},{"title":"Sample Size Estimation - Compare Two Proportions","url":"https://www2.ccrb.cuhk.edu.hk/stat/proportion/Casagrande.htm"},{"title":"Pertussis Challenge Study in Adults Vaccinated With BPZE1","url":"https://cdn.clinicaltrials.gov/large-docs/31/NCT05461131/SAP_001.pdf"},{"title":"Sample size estimation v. 2018-02","url":"https://www.bioinformatics.babraham.ac.uk/training/Introduction_to_Power_Analysis/Sample%20Size%20estimation%20Course%20slides.pdf"},{"title":"Power and Sample Size Determination - sph.bu.edu","url":"https://sphweb.bumc.bu.edu/otlt/mph-modules/bs/bs704_power/BS704_Power8.html"},{"title":"Sample Size Calculation: Power, Errors & Clinical Trials | IntuitionLabs","url":"https://intuitionlabs.ai/articles/sample-size-calculation-clinical-trials"},{"title":"Sample Size Calculator & Statistical Power Calculator","url":"https://www.gigacalculator.com/calculators/power-sample-size-calculator.php"},{"title":"ADJUnct Semaglutide Treatment in Type 1 Diabetes","url":"https://cdn.clinicaltrials.gov/large-docs/33/NCT05537233/Prot_SAP_001.pdf"}]},"I've found relevant information about sample size calculations for comparing two proportions with 80% power. Here's what the search results show:\n\n## Key Concepts\n\nIf your power is 80%, then this means that you have a 20% probability of failing to detect a significant difference when one does exist, i.e., a false negative result (otherwise known as type II error).\n\n## Sample Size Calculation Approach\n\nFor a power of 80%, β is 0.2 and the critical value is 0.84, and this is used in calculations with the expected sample proportions of the two groups.\n\n## Practical Examples\n\nThe search results include several examples:\n\n1. If aiming for a decrease from 40% to 10% for tumour development, approximately 2 samples of about 36 subjects would be needed to reach significance (p<0.05) with 80% power.\n\n2. Using Fisher's exact test at an alpha level of 0.05, a sample size of 32 per group is expected to have power close to 80% to detect a 30% difference in the proportion of participants if the proportion in the control group is 5%.\n\nThe results also reference comprehensive references like Machin et al. (2009) \"Sample size tables for clinical studies,\" which contains detailed tables for various combinations of Type I and Type II error levels. For specific tables with varying absolute differences, you may want to consult that reference or use statistical software like G*Power, Stata, or online calculators that can generate tables for your specific parameters."],"durationSeconds":10.828778959000482,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"106ed2e3-9fed-4b4b-9137-8121d913156a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
