{"parentUuid":"909d45d2-4247-40e1-8572-effb5ba27777","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01X5An8Fn5isnXXSkZ5SSQUn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01D767PqiujTSD922DSD87Rj","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"paired bootstrap confidence interval number of resamples B 2000 10000 proportion"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3836,"cache_read_input_tokens":12323,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3836,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqKn6VWoxr3Ybzjw7hZ","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"b0bcdd5e-d80e-47be-bd15-5f760db47431","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:09.857Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"909d45d2-4247-40e1-8572-effb5ba27777","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019SBWjFM8GEr7rn5rR7URnc","type":"tool_result","content":"# Sample Size Formula for McNemar Test (Dependent Proportions)\n\n## Formula\n\nFor within-subjects studies comparing dependent proportions:\n\n**n = z²(p₁₂ + p₂₁)/d²**\n\nWhere:\n- z = sum of z-values for confidence level and power\n- p₁₂ + p₂₁ = sum of discordant proportions\n- d = smallest effect size to detect\n\n## Key Parameter Values\n\nBased on analysis of 50 real-world studies, recommended discordant proportion estimates:\n- **Typical**: 0.22 (median value)\n- **Conservative**: 0.28 (75th percentile)\n\n## Sample Size Examples (95% Confidence, 80% Power)\n\n| Effect Size | p_discordant = 0.22 | p_discordant = 0.28 |\n|------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| 10%       | 343               | 436               |\n| 15%       | 151               | 192               |\n| 20%       | 84                | 107               |\n| 30%       | 38                | 47                |\n\n## Key Finding\n\n\"Sample size estimates for dependent proportions are consistently smaller than those for proportions from two independent groups.\" For typical discordant proportions (0.22) with effect sizes ≤30%, within-subjects sample sizes are approximately 44% of between-subjects requirements."}]},"uuid":"b5f64d90-73a5-4b68-a1f7-5e1ddad92079","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:17.289Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":391535,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Sample Size Formula for McNemar Test (Dependent Proportions)\n\n## Formula\n\nFor within-subjects studies comparing dependent proportions:\n\n**n = z²(p₁₂ + p₂₁)/d²**\n\nWhere:\n- z = sum of z-values for confidence level and power\n- p₁₂ + p₂₁ = sum of discordant proportions\n- d = smallest effect size to detect\n\n## Key Parameter Values\n\nBased on analysis of 50 real-world studies, recommended discordant proportion estimates:\n- **Typical**: 0.22 (median value)\n- **Conservative**: 0.28 (75th percentile)\n\n## Sample Size Examples (95% Confidence, 80% Power)\n\n| Effect Size | p_discordant = 0.22 | p_discordant = 0.28 |\n|------------|-------------------|-------------------|\n| 10%       | 343               | 436               |\n| 15%       | 151               | 192               |\n| 20%       | 84                | 107               |\n| 30%       | 38                | 47                |\n\n## Key Finding\n\n\"Sample size estimates for dependent proportions are consistently smaller than those for proportions from two independent groups.\" For typical discordant proportions (0.22) with effect sizes ≤30%, within-subjects sample sizes are approximately 44% of between-subjects requirements.","durationMs":7815,"url":"https://measuringu.com/sample-sizes-for-the-mcnemar-test/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"909d45d2-4247-40e1-8572-effb5ba27777","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b0bcdd5e-d80e-47be-bd15-5f760db47431","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01D767PqiujTSD922DSD87Rj","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"paired bootstrap confidence interval number of resamples B 2000 10000 proportion\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Bootstrap Confidence Interval Calculator | Statistics.tools\",\"url\":\"https://statistics.tools/bootstrap-ci-calculator\"},{\"title\":\"Contrastive Decoding for Synthetic Data Generation in Low-Resource Language Modeling\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.08245\"},{\"title\":\"Bootstrap Estimates of Confidence Intervals | UVA Library\",\"url\":\"https://library.virginia.edu/data/articles/bootstrap-estimates-of-confidence-intervals\"},{\"title\":\"Bootstrapping – Another Approach to Confidence Intervals\",\"url\":\"https://stat20.berkeley.edu/fall-2024/3-generalization/09-bootstrapping/notes.html\"},{\"title\":\"To Ship or Not to Ship: An Extensive Evaluation of Automatic Metrics for   Machine Translation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.10821\"},{\"title\":\"What's the Price of Monotonicity? A Multi-Dataset Benchmark of Monotone-Constrained Gradient Boosting for Credit PD\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.17945\"},{\"title\":\"Chapter 7 Confidence intervals with bootstrapping | Modern Statistical Methods for Psychology\",\"url\":\"https://bookdown.org/gregcox7/ims_psych/foundations-bootstrapping.html\"},{\"title\":\"An Information Theoretic Approach Towards Assessing Perceptual Audio   Quality using EEG\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1509.03937\"},{\"title\":\"Moderating the Mediation Bootstrap for Causal Inference\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.11285\"},{\"title\":\"SNAP-UQ: Self-supervised Next-Activation Prediction for Single-Pass Uncertainty in TinyML\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.12907\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding paired bootstrap confidence intervals and the number of resamples (B):\n\n## Recommended Number of Resamples\n\nChoose at least 1000 resamples for CIs, 2000+ for BCa (the bias-corrected and accelerated method).\n\nA rule of thumb for the number of resamples needed for a reasonable bootstrap distribution is 10,000, though specific applications may vary.\n\n## Paired Bootstrap for Confidence Intervals\n\nFor paired data, resample pairs. This means that when you have paired observations, you should maintain the pairing structure during resampling rather than resampling observations independently.\n\nThe examples in the search results show various applications using different values of B:\n- One study used paired bootstrap with B=1000 resamples to calculate confidence intervals\n- Another created 10,000 resamples by drawing system pairs with replacements\n- Another used nonparametric bootstrap with 1,000 resamples to form 95% confidence intervals\n\nThe choice between B=2000, B=10000, and other values depends on your specific needs, but generally, use at least 1000 resamples, with more resamples providing better accuracy in the tail areas of the distribution.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"a1c191db-009b-4936-8025-f09ea8aa34ef","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:18.345Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"paired bootstrap confidence interval number of resamples B 2000 10000 proportion","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01RgBTKRmv6murrcaSdA4CAE","content":[{"title":"Bootstrap Confidence Interval Calculator | Statistics.tools","url":"https://statistics.tools/bootstrap-ci-calculator"},{"title":"Contrastive Decoding for Synthetic Data Generation in Low-Resource Language Modeling","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.08245"},{"title":"Bootstrap Estimates of Confidence Intervals | UVA Library","url":"https://library.virginia.edu/data/articles/bootstrap-estimates-of-confidence-intervals"},{"title":"Bootstrapping – Another Approach to Confidence Intervals","url":"https://stat20.berkeley.edu/fall-2024/3-generalization/09-bootstrapping/notes.html"},{"title":"To Ship or Not to Ship: An Extensive Evaluation of Automatic Metrics for   Machine Translation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.10821"},{"title":"What's the Price of Monotonicity? A Multi-Dataset Benchmark of Monotone-Constrained Gradient Boosting for Credit PD","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.17945"},{"title":"Chapter 7 Confidence intervals with bootstrapping | Modern Statistical Methods for Psychology","url":"https://bookdown.org/gregcox7/ims_psych/foundations-bootstrapping.html"},{"title":"An Information Theoretic Approach Towards Assessing Perceptual Audio   Quality using EEG","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1509.03937"},{"title":"Moderating the Mediation Bootstrap for Causal Inference","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.11285"},{"title":"SNAP-UQ: Self-supervised Next-Activation Prediction for Single-Pass Uncertainty in TinyML","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.12907"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding paired bootstrap confidence intervals and the number of resamples (B):\n\n## Recommended Number of Resamples\n\nChoose at least 1000 resamples for CIs, 2000+ for BCa (the bias-corrected and accelerated method).\n\nA rule of thumb for the number of resamples needed for a reasonable bootstrap distribution is 10,000, though specific applications may vary.\n\n## Paired Bootstrap for Confidence Intervals\n\nFor paired data, resample pairs. This means that when you have paired observations, you should maintain the pairing structure during resampling rather than resampling observations independently.\n\nThe examples in the search results show various applications using different values of B:\n- One study used paired bootstrap with B=1000 resamples to calculate confidence intervals\n- Another created 10,000 resamples by drawing system pairs with replacements\n- Another used nonparametric bootstrap with 1,000 resamples to form 95% confidence intervals\n\nThe choice between B=2000, B=10000, and other values depends on your specific needs, but generally, use at least 1000 resamples, with more resamples providing better accuracy in the tail areas of the distribution."],"durationSeconds":8.320234915999695,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b0bcdd5e-d80e-47be-bd15-5f760db47431","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
