{"parentUuid":"637692c8-9f5a-4b3d-9aff-d7cd9a427a50","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015HJML2rHpwdVkVyxCR4VUP","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"power difference two proportions rule of thumb 16/effect size squared\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"power twoproportions — Power analysis for a two-sample proportions test\",\"url\":\"https://www.stata.com/manuals/pss-2powertwoproportions.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Effect size calculator - Cohen's d, Cohen's h, Phi(φ), R squared, Eta squared.\",\"url\":\"https://www.statskingdom.com/effect-size-calculator.html\"},{\"title\":\"Rules of thumb on magnitudes of effect sizes\",\"url\":\"https://imaging.mrc-cbu.cam.ac.uk/statswiki/FAQ/effectSize\"},{\"title\":\"PS: Cohen h and h'\",\"url\":\"https://peterstatistics.com/Terms/EffectSizes/CohenH.html\"},{\"title\":\"Tests for Two Proportions using Effect Size\",\"url\":\"https://www.ncss.com/wp-content/themes/ncss/pdf/Procedures/PASS/Tests_for_Two_Proportions_using_Effect_Size.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Bayesian two-interval test\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.01271\"},{\"title\":\"Power analysis for comparison of proportions | Stata\",\"url\":\"https://www.stata.com/features/overview/power-analysis-for-proportions/\"}]\n\nI found search results related to power analysis for two proportions and effect sizes, but the results don't directly contain information about the specific rule of thumb \"16/effect size squared\" for power difference in two proportions tests. \n\nThe search results discuss:\n- Effect size as the difference between the experimental-group proportion and the control-group proportion\n- Cohen's h effect size (h = φ1 - φ2, where φᵢ = 2 × ArcSine(√Pᵢ)) for comparing proportions\n- Various statistical software approaches to power analysis\n\nHowever, the specific formula \"16/effect size squared\" that you mentioned in your query does not appear in these results. This may be a rule of thumb from a specific textbook or statistical reference that wasn't captured in this search. If you're looking for more information about this particular formula, you might want to check Cohen's statistical power analysis references or consult specialized power analysis textbooks.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"558221f7-c9b6-4592-814b-1d0ad14b3997","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:30.195Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"power difference two proportions rule of thumb 16/effect size squared","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_011viBVF38dtveidKZDtPjP4","content":[{"title":"power twoproportions — Power analysis for a two-sample proportions test","url":"https://www.stata.com/manuals/pss-2powertwoproportions.pdf"},{"title":"Effect size calculator - Cohen's d, Cohen's h, Phi(φ), R squared, Eta squared.","url":"https://www.statskingdom.com/effect-size-calculator.html"},{"title":"Rules of thumb on magnitudes of effect sizes","url":"https://imaging.mrc-cbu.cam.ac.uk/statswiki/FAQ/effectSize"},{"title":"PS: Cohen h and h'","url":"https://peterstatistics.com/Terms/EffectSizes/CohenH.html"},{"title":"Tests for Two Proportions using Effect Size","url":"https://www.ncss.com/wp-content/themes/ncss/pdf/Procedures/PASS/Tests_for_Two_Proportions_using_Effect_Size.pdf"},{"title":"Bayesian two-interval test","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.01271"},{"title":"Power analysis for comparison of proportions | Stata","url":"https://www.stata.com/features/overview/power-analysis-for-proportions/"}]},"I found search results related to power analysis for two proportions and effect sizes, but the results don't directly contain information about the specific rule of thumb \"16/effect size squared\" for power difference in two proportions tests. \n\nThe search results discuss:\n- Effect size as the difference between the experimental-group proportion and the control-group proportion\n- Cohen's h effect size (h = φ1 - φ2, where φᵢ = 2 × ArcSine(√Pᵢ)) for comparing proportions\n- Various statistical software approaches to power analysis\n\nHowever, the specific formula \"16/effect size squared\" that you mentioned in your query does not appear in these results. This may be a rule of thumb from a specific textbook or statistical reference that wasn't captured in this search. If you're looking for more information about this particular formula, you might want to check Cohen's statistical power analysis references or consult specialized power analysis textbooks."],"durationSeconds":5.328664874999784,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"637692c8-9f5a-4b3d-9aff-d7cd9a427a50","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"dbfe6d1b-3890-4f5e-99e3-4a5ebe685580","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KzSDxukkaeyAB7L8qy4GkD","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"number of bootstrap replications affect Monte Carlo error confidence interval B=2000 recommendation\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"The automatic construction of bootstrap confidence intervals - PMC\",\"url\":\"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7958418/\"},{\"title\":\"Bootstrap confidence interval variations – James E. Pustejovsky\",\"url\":\"https://jepusto.com/posts/Bootstrap-CI-variations/\"},{\"title\":\"Better bootstrap 𝑡 confidence intervals for the mean\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.10083v2\"},{\"title\":\"Simulating bootstrap confidence intervals – James E. Pustejovsky\",\"url\":\"https://jepusto.com/posts/Simulating-bootstrap-CIs/\"},{\"title\":\"Bootstrap Inference for Multiple Imputation under Uncongeniality and   Misspecification\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1911.09980\"},{\"title\":\"Confidence intervals of prediction accuracy measures for multivariable   prediction models based on the bootstrap-based optimism correction methods\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2005.01457\"},{\"title\":\"Quantifying Uncertainty: All We Need is the Bootstrap?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.20182\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding the number of bootstrap replications and Monte Carlo error in confidence intervals:\n\n## B=2000 Recommendation\n\nB = 2000 was found to be sufficient and not greatly wasteful in bootstrap confidence interval applications. The research compared this against smaller values, noting that stopping at B=1000 would magnify the Monte Carlo error by about √2, perhaps becoming uncomfortably large at the lower bootstrap confidence limits.\n\n## General Recommendations\n\nThe literature provides guidance on minimum bootstrap replications for different purposes:\n\n- The number of replications B is generally recommended to be at least 200 for variance estimation and at least 1,000 for percentile based intervals\n- A sufficient number of replications is required, ideally more than 1000 in practice when outer bootstraps are used for quantile estimation\n- B = 1000 is generally considered enough based on recommendations and choices in simulation studies\n\n## How Number of Replications Affects Monte Carlo Error\n\nEstimates of interval endpoints Monte Carlo errors can help guide the choice of the number of bootstrap replications B necessary for reasonable accuracy. The Monte Carlo error in bootstrap confidence intervals decreases as B increases, with the practical trade-off between computational cost and acceptable error levels being a key consideration in choosing B.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"5b52ccf8-aaad-421b-9361-ffa8c86d6619","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:31.030Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"number of bootstrap replications affect Monte Carlo error confidence interval B=2000 recommendation","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Er43gohEuNRyLQUPyPFpur","content":[{"title":"The automatic construction of bootstrap confidence intervals - PMC","url":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7958418/"},{"title":"Bootstrap confidence interval variations – James E. Pustejovsky","url":"https://jepusto.com/posts/Bootstrap-CI-variations/"},{"title":"Better bootstrap 𝑡 confidence intervals for the mean","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2508.10083v2"},{"title":"Simulating bootstrap confidence intervals – James E. Pustejovsky","url":"https://jepusto.com/posts/Simulating-bootstrap-CIs/"},{"title":"Bootstrap Inference for Multiple Imputation under Uncongeniality and   Misspecification","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1911.09980"},{"title":"Confidence intervals of prediction accuracy measures for multivariable   prediction models based on the bootstrap-based optimism correction methods","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2005.01457"},{"title":"Quantifying Uncertainty: All We Need is the Bootstrap?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2403.20182"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding the number of bootstrap replications and Monte Carlo error in confidence intervals:\n\n## B=2000 Recommendation\n\nB = 2000 was found to be sufficient and not greatly wasteful in bootstrap confidence interval applications. The research compared this against smaller values, noting that stopping at B=1000 would magnify the Monte Carlo error by about √2, perhaps becoming uncomfortably large at the lower bootstrap confidence limits.\n\n## General Recommendations\n\nThe literature provides guidance on minimum bootstrap replications for different purposes:\n\n- The number of replications B is generally recommended to be at least 200 for variance estimation and at least 1,000 for percentile based intervals\n- A sufficient number of replications is required, ideally more than 1000 in practice when outer bootstraps are used for quantile estimation\n- B = 1000 is generally considered enough based on recommendations and choices in simulation studies\n\n## How Number of Replications Affects Monte Carlo Error\n\nEstimates of interval endpoints Monte Carlo errors can help guide the choice of the number of bootstrap replications B necessary for reasonable accuracy. The Monte Carlo error in bootstrap confidence intervals decreases as B increases, with the practical trade-off between computational cost and acceptable error levels being a key consideration in choosing B."],"durationSeconds":6.7306814580000935,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"dbfe6d1b-3890-4f5e-99e3-4a5ebe685580","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
