{"parentUuid":"4d227e2e-b437-433f-93e3-b0cdcdccbc06","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01L8EsLrSjeCRRk448sG76kV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SNF5BCDYShvU4fXSLsH3ET","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://jepusto.com/posts/Simulating-bootstrap-CIs/","prompt":"Extract any guidance or recommendation on how many bootstrap resamples B are needed for confidence intervals, and how Monte Carlo error scales with B."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1141,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1623,"cache_read_input_tokens":18317,"output_tokens":510,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1623},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1141,"output_tokens":510,"cache_read_input_tokens":18317,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1623,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1623,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqModpXZvBRqkK31wtX","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"2ba340ec-7e79-48c3-961b-e139509fb148","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:38.270Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"98ef1231-9bd5-45da-9fa0-97fc845ad9a7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BR1jFBMLgJ9Vqaa1kPttks","type":"tool_result","content":"# Sample Size Formula for Comparing Two Proportions\n\n## Formula\n\nThe calculator uses this equation:\n\n\"n = (Zα/2+Zβ)² * (p1(1-p1)+p2(1-p2)) / (p1-p2)²\"\n\nWhere:\n- Zα/2 = critical value at α/2 (1.96 for 95% confidence)\n- Zβ = critical value at β (0.84 for 80% power)\n- p1, p2 = expected sample proportions for each group\n\n## Worked Example\n\nThe page provides one concrete example: A supermarket promotion study comparing current product uptake of 15% versus a desired increase to 25%.\n\n**Result:** \"248 customers who have received the promotional material and 248 who have not\" are needed to detect this difference at 95% confidence level and 80% power.\n\nThis represents:\n- **Baseline proportion (p1):** 15%\n- **Target proportion (p2):** 25%\n- **Absolute difference:** 10 percentage points\n- **Sample size per group:** 248"}]},"uuid":"1bd07f54-3e27-4b5d-9d28-230dafb0447c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:40.882Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":94290,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Sample Size Formula for Comparing Two Proportions\n\n## Formula\n\nThe calculator uses this equation:\n\n\"n = (Zα/2+Zβ)² * (p1(1-p1)+p2(1-p2)) / (p1-p2)²\"\n\nWhere:\n- Zα/2 = critical value at α/2 (1.96 for 95% confidence)\n- Zβ = critical value at β (0.84 for 80% power)\n- p1, p2 = expected sample proportions for each group\n\n## Worked Example\n\nThe page provides one concrete example: A supermarket promotion study comparing current product uptake of 15% versus a desired increase to 25%.\n\n**Result:** \"248 customers who have received the promotional material and 248 who have not\" are needed to detect this difference at 95% confidence level and 80% power.\n\nThis represents:\n- **Baseline proportion (p1):** 15%\n- **Target proportion (p2):** 25%\n- **Absolute difference:** 10 percentage points\n- **Sample size per group:** 248","durationMs":5050,"url":"https://select-statistics.co.uk/calculators/sample-size-calculator-two-proportions/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"98ef1231-9bd5-45da-9fa0-97fc845ad9a7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"4d227e2e-b437-433f-93e3-b0cdcdccbc06","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01V1i43q7RVR9E5txEyMrEbz","type":"tool_result","content":"# Sample Size Calculation for Comparing Two Proportions\n\n## Formula Components\n\nBased on the MedCalc documentation, the calculation requires:\n\n- **Type I error (α)**: Probability of rejecting a true null hypothesis\n- **Type II error (β)**: Probability of accepting a false null hypothesis\n- **Proportion in Group 1**: First hypothesized proportion\n- **Proportion in Group 2**: Second hypothesized proportion\n- **Sample size ratio**: Relationship between group 1 and group 2 sample sizes\n- **Statistical test**: Chi-squared test or Fisher's exact test\n\n## Worked Example\n\nThe documentation provides this example scenario:\n\n- Minimum detectable difference: 15 percentage points\n- Group 1 proportion: 75%\n- Group 2 proportion: 60%\n- Sample size ratio: 2:1 (Group 1 has twice as many cases)\n- α-level: 0.05 (two-sided)\n- β-level: 0.20 (80% power)\n- Test: Chi-squared\n\n**Result**: \"the required sample size, which is 224 in the first group and 112 in the second group, i.e. 336 cases in total.\"\n\n## Note\n\nThe document does not explicitly display the mathematical formula itself; it describes the input parameters and output based on the Machin et al. (2009) reference."}]},"uuid":"37fc77e5-76bc-44e4-a02c-08de6801a1b4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:41.778Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":11216,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Sample Size Calculation for Comparing Two Proportions\n\n## Formula Components\n\nBased on the MedCalc documentation, the calculation requires:\n\n- **Type I error (α)**: Probability of rejecting a true null hypothesis\n- **Type II error (β)**: Probability of accepting a false null hypothesis\n- **Proportion in Group 1**: First hypothesized proportion\n- **Proportion in Group 2**: Second hypothesized proportion\n- **Sample size ratio**: Relationship between group 1 and group 2 sample sizes\n- **Statistical test**: Chi-squared test or Fisher's exact test\n\n## Worked Example\n\nThe documentation provides this example scenario:\n\n- Minimum detectable difference: 15 percentage points\n- Group 1 proportion: 75%\n- Group 2 proportion: 60%\n- Sample size ratio: 2:1 (Group 1 has twice as many cases)\n- α-level: 0.05 (two-sided)\n- β-level: 0.20 (80% power)\n- Test: Chi-squared\n\n**Result**: \"the required sample size, which is 224 in the first group and 112 in the second group, i.e. 336 cases in total.\"\n\n## Note\n\nThe document does not explicitly display the mathematical formula itself; it describes the input parameters and output based on the Machin et al. (2009) reference.","durationMs":4514,"url":"https://www.medcalc.org/en/manual/sample-size-comparison-of-proportions.php"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4d227e2e-b437-433f-93e3-b0cdcdccbc06","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"2ba340ec-7e79-48c3-961b-e139509fb148","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SNF5BCDYShvU4fXSLsH3ET","type":"tool_result","content":"# Bootstrap Sample Size Guidance\n\n## Key Recommendations\n\nThe document doesn't provide explicit guidance on specific B values needed for confidence intervals. However, it references practical choices: practitioners might use \"something more like B = 1999 or 3999\" when applying bootstrap methods in practice, versus smaller values like B = 399 in simulations.\n\n## Monte Carlo Error and B\n\nThe relationship between bootstrap sample size and simulation properties is empirical rather than theoretical here. The author demonstrates that:\n\n- Coverage rates and interval widths are \"meaningfully affected by the number of bootstraps\"\n- Linear relationships exist between performance metrics and 1/B, allowing extrapolation to infinite bootstrap samples\n- The choice of B creates a practical trade-off: \"larger number of booties...simulations will take forever to finish...or we'll have to cut down on the number of conditions\"\n\n## Computational Consideration\n\nThe extrapolation technique proposed by Boos & Zhang (2000) sidesteps the B-selection problem by using multiple subsample sizes and linear regression to estimate B = ∞ properties, rather than prescribing an optimal single value.\n\nThe document focuses on *computational efficiency* rather than statistical guidance for practitioners choosing B for their own analyses."}]},"uuid":"e82a4fa2-870f-4b02-bd16-5f02ac025fcc","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:44.899Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":157063,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Bootstrap Sample Size Guidance\n\n## Key Recommendations\n\nThe document doesn't provide explicit guidance on specific B values needed for confidence intervals. However, it references practical choices: practitioners might use \"something more like B = 1999 or 3999\" when applying bootstrap methods in practice, versus smaller values like B = 399 in simulations.\n\n## Monte Carlo Error and B\n\nThe relationship between bootstrap sample size and simulation properties is empirical rather than theoretical here. The author demonstrates that:\n\n- Coverage rates and interval widths are \"meaningfully affected by the number of bootstraps\"\n- Linear relationships exist between performance metrics and 1/B, allowing extrapolation to infinite bootstrap samples\n- The choice of B creates a practical trade-off: \"larger number of booties...simulations will take forever to finish...or we'll have to cut down on the number of conditions\"\n\n## Computational Consideration\n\nThe extrapolation technique proposed by Boos & Zhang (2000) sidesteps the B-selection problem by using multiple subsample sizes and linear regression to estimate B = ∞ properties, rather than prescribing an optimal single value.\n\nThe document focuses on *computational efficiency* rather than statistical guidance for practitioners choosing B for their own analyses.","durationMs":6222,"url":"https://jepusto.com/posts/Simulating-bootstrap-CIs/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2ba340ec-7e79-48c3-961b-e139509fb148","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
