{"parentUuid":"cfe8cb82-4b4d-46d0-8b2e-c426747f8b65","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01EWFYY4LxLjfTakhQzhBH7t","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018Rv8zxLgZKiYi5uWBqqfPV","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"Connor 1987 sample size McNemar paired binary odds ratio discordant proportion formula"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2930,"cache_read_input_tokens":19940,"output_tokens":236,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2930},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":236,"cache_read_input_tokens":19940,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2930,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2930,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqNpuzga5Qnh6QfVcps","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"bd5b9613-09cc-44c7-bd56-e17a29d04743","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:49.807Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"cfe8cb82-4b4d-46d0-8b2e-c426747f8b65","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HFaQok6MYxyjwjxFJkD4cj","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"bootstrap confidence interval width proportion scales 1/sqrt(n) standard error\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Lesson 6: Introduction to the Bootstrap\",\"url\":\"http://courses.washington.edu/matlab1/Lesson_6.html\"},{\"title\":\"Better bootstrap t confidence intervals for the mean\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.10083\"},{\"title\":\"Network driven sampling; a critical threshold for design effects\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1505.05461\"},{\"title\":\"Chapter 8 Estimation, Confidence Intervals, and Bootstrapping | Statistical Inference via Data Science\",\"url\":\"https://moderndive.com/v2/confidence-intervals.html\"},{\"title\":\"Bootstrapping a Proportion - Probably Overthinking It\",\"url\":\"https://www.allendowney.com/blog/2024/10/15/bootstrapping-a-proportion/\"},{\"title\":\"Bootstrap confidence interval variations – James E. Pustejovsky\",\"url\":\"https://jepusto.com/posts/Bootstrap-CI-variations/\"},{\"title\":\"A Cheap Bootstrap Method for Fast Inference\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2202.00090\"},{\"title\":\"What Teachers Should Know about the Bootstrap: Resampling in the   Undergraduate Statistics Curriculum\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1411.5279\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found relevant information about how bootstrap confidence interval widths scale with sample size:\n\n## Bootstrap Confidence Interval Width Scaling\n\nThe margin of error in confidence intervals decreases proportional to the square root of the sample size. More specifically, for a sample of size 25, 1/√25 = 0.2, and if we draw a sample of size 100, 1/√100 = 0.1, illustrating the 1/√n relationship.\n\nFor bootstrap methods specifically, bootstrap distributions tend to be too narrow, by a factor of √((n-1)/n) for the mean; the theoretical bootstrap standard error is s_B = σ̂/√n = √((n-1)/n)(s/√n).\n\nAdditionally, the Central Limit Theorem states that for sufficiently large data sets, the mean should be pulled from a normal distribution that has a standard deviation that shrinks by a factor of 1/sqrt(n) where n is the size of the data set.\n\nFor a more general picture, the half-width for large sample size n has mean given by approximately t_{B,1-α/2} √(2/B) Γ((B+1)/2)/Γ(B/2) σ/√n, confirming the fundamental 1/√n scaling relationship in the asymptotic behavior of bootstrap confidence intervals.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"3eb8d68c-6c2f-44c4-8a29-0aff7a353923","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:56.534Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"bootstrap confidence interval width proportion scales 1/sqrt(n) standard error","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Gvbw1wqFhbZM69phv1pUxJ","content":[{"title":"Lesson 6: Introduction to the Bootstrap","url":"http://courses.washington.edu/matlab1/Lesson_6.html"},{"title":"Better bootstrap t confidence intervals for the mean","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2508.10083"},{"title":"Network driven sampling; a critical threshold for design effects","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1505.05461"},{"title":"Chapter 8 Estimation, Confidence Intervals, and Bootstrapping | Statistical Inference via Data Science","url":"https://moderndive.com/v2/confidence-intervals.html"},{"title":"Bootstrapping a Proportion - Probably Overthinking It","url":"https://www.allendowney.com/blog/2024/10/15/bootstrapping-a-proportion/"},{"title":"Bootstrap confidence interval variations – James E. Pustejovsky","url":"https://jepusto.com/posts/Bootstrap-CI-variations/"},{"title":"A Cheap Bootstrap Method for Fast Inference","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2202.00090"},{"title":"What Teachers Should Know about the Bootstrap: Resampling in the   Undergraduate Statistics Curriculum","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1411.5279"}]},"Based on the search results, I found relevant information about how bootstrap confidence interval widths scale with sample size:\n\n## Bootstrap Confidence Interval Width Scaling\n\nThe margin of error in confidence intervals decreases proportional to the square root of the sample size. More specifically, for a sample of size 25, 1/√25 = 0.2, and if we draw a sample of size 100, 1/√100 = 0.1, illustrating the 1/√n relationship.\n\nFor bootstrap methods specifically, bootstrap distributions tend to be too narrow, by a factor of √((n-1)/n) for the mean; the theoretical bootstrap standard error is s_B = σ̂/√n = √((n-1)/n)(s/√n).\n\nAdditionally, the Central Limit Theorem states that for sufficiently large data sets, the mean should be pulled from a normal distribution that has a standard deviation that shrinks by a factor of 1/sqrt(n) where n is the size of the data set.\n\nFor a more general picture, the half-width for large sample size n has mean given by approximately t_{B,1-α/2} √(2/B) Γ((B+1)/2)/Γ(B/2) σ/√n, confirming the fundamental 1/√n scaling relationship in the asymptotic behavior of bootstrap confidence intervals."],"durationSeconds":6.982119459000416,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"cfe8cb82-4b4d-46d0-8b2e-c426747f8b65","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"bd5b9613-09cc-44c7-bd56-e17a29d04743","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018Rv8zxLgZKiYi5uWBqqfPV","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Connor 1987 sample size McNemar paired binary odds ratio discordant proportion formula\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Sample Size for McNemar's Paired Test Calculator\",\"url\":\"https://metricgate.com/docs/sample-size-mcnemar-paired/\"},{\"title\":\"proportions.mcnemar: Power Analysis for McNemar's Exact Test (Paired Proportions) in pwrss: Statistical Power and Sample Size Calculation Tools\",\"url\":\"https://rdrr.io/cran/pwrss/man/proportions.mcnemar.html\"},{\"title\":\"How to Calculate Sample Size for McNemar's Test (Paired Proportions) - PowerAndSampleSize\",\"url\":\"https://powerandsamplesize.com/tutorial/how-to-calculate-sample-size-mcnemars-test/\"},{\"title\":\"Power analysis for a two-sample paired-proportions test\",\"url\":\"https://www.stata.com/manuals/pss-2powerpairedproportions.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"With Little Power Comes Great Responsibility\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2010.06595\"},{\"title\":\"PASS Sample Size Software NCSS.com 150-1 © NCSS, LLC. All Rights Reserved.\",\"url\":\"https://www.ncss.com/wp-content/themes/ncss/pdf/Procedures/PASS/Tests_for_Two_Correlated_Proportions-McNemar_Test.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Breast/Evaluation of Cryotherapy and TRPA1 Receptors in Chemotherapy Induced Neuropathy\",\"url\":\"https://cdn.clinicaltrials.gov/large-docs/31/NCT03329131/Prot_SAP_000.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Calculate The Sample Size for McNemar's Test - Accredited Professional Statistician For Hire\",\"url\":\"https://www.scalestatistics.com/sample-size-for-mcnemars-test.html\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found information about Connor's 1987 work on McNemar's test sample size calculations:\n\nConnor's (1987) formula for required sample size is: n = (z1-α/2√pd + z1-β√(pd - pd²(1-(OR-1)²/(OR+1)²))), where:\n\n- **pd** represents the discordance probability (p12 + p21), which is the probability that a pair is discordant (the two binary outcomes differ)\n- **OR** (odds ratio) is defined as p21/p12, which specifies the asymmetry between the two types of discordant pairs under the alternative hypothesis\n\nThe formula demonstrates that since only discordant pairs contribute information to McNemar's test, the effective sample size for the test is n × pd (the expected number of discordant pairs). A lower discordance probability means fewer informative pairs, requiring a larger total sample n to maintain the desired power.\n\nThis approach is commonly used in statistical software for power and sample size calculations for paired binary outcomes, particularly in crossover trials and matched studies.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"81b8136e-8619-49ed-b858-34e859dbd798","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:03.307Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Connor 1987 sample size McNemar paired binary odds ratio discordant proportion formula","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01AFsunQYucSy4TLKkexXCrC","content":[{"title":"Sample Size for McNemar's Paired Test Calculator","url":"https://metricgate.com/docs/sample-size-mcnemar-paired/"},{"title":"proportions.mcnemar: Power Analysis for McNemar's Exact Test (Paired Proportions) in pwrss: Statistical Power and Sample Size Calculation Tools","url":"https://rdrr.io/cran/pwrss/man/proportions.mcnemar.html"},{"title":"How to Calculate Sample Size for McNemar's Test (Paired Proportions) - PowerAndSampleSize","url":"https://powerandsamplesize.com/tutorial/how-to-calculate-sample-size-mcnemars-test/"},{"title":"Power analysis for a two-sample paired-proportions test","url":"https://www.stata.com/manuals/pss-2powerpairedproportions.pdf"},{"title":"With Little Power Comes Great Responsibility","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2010.06595"},{"title":"PASS Sample Size Software NCSS.com 150-1 © NCSS, LLC. All Rights Reserved.","url":"https://www.ncss.com/wp-content/themes/ncss/pdf/Procedures/PASS/Tests_for_Two_Correlated_Proportions-McNemar_Test.pdf"},{"title":"Breast/Evaluation of Cryotherapy and TRPA1 Receptors in Chemotherapy Induced Neuropathy","url":"https://cdn.clinicaltrials.gov/large-docs/31/NCT03329131/Prot_SAP_000.pdf"},{"title":"Calculate The Sample Size for McNemar's Test - Accredited Professional Statistician For Hire","url":"https://www.scalestatistics.com/sample-size-for-mcnemars-test.html"}]},"Based on the search results, I found information about Connor's 1987 work on McNemar's test sample size calculations:\n\nConnor's (1987) formula for required sample size is: n = (z1-α/2√pd + z1-β√(pd - pd²(1-(OR-1)²/(OR+1)²))), where:\n\n- **pd** represents the discordance probability (p12 + p21), which is the probability that a pair is discordant (the two binary outcomes differ)\n- **OR** (odds ratio) is defined as p21/p12, which specifies the asymmetry between the two types of discordant pairs under the alternative hypothesis\n\nThe formula demonstrates that since only discordant pairs contribute information to McNemar's test, the effective sample size for the test is n × pd (the expected number of discordant pairs). A lower discordance probability means fewer informative pairs, requiring a larger total sample n to maintain the desired power.\n\nThis approach is commonly used in statistical software for power and sample size calculations for paired binary outcomes, particularly in crossover trials and matched studies."],"durationSeconds":13.333763249999844,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bd5b9613-09cc-44c7-bd56-e17a29d04743","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
